metadata.name: Representation #31
metadata.description:
Explore the world of gender politics through vibrant circles.

Representation is an artwork/data visualization about the gender split in parliaments across the world. 

Each minted artwork gets assigned 6 countries from different regions. 1 country from the Pacific, 1 from Europe, 1 from Asia, 1 from the Americas, 1 from Sub-saharan Africa and 1 from the Middle East and North Africa.

Each circle in your artwork represents the gender split of the parliament(s) in one of those countries by using colors. The legend in the bottom right can be used to decipher which color means what.

This artwork was created using p5js.

The artwork adapts to different screen sizes and ratios, so I exploring it on various devices or resizing your browser window. 

Features:

- Circle Size: What size are the circles?
- Circle Distance: How far apart from each other are the circles?
- Circle Scatter: Are the circles scattered on the Y-axis?

twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art

metadata.name: Visa to the stars #321
metadata.description:
Generative space scenes with an illustrative look.

Use the capture functions to export in big after opening it in its own window, the artwork is full of details.

Press SPACE to show/hide the menu

Control the camera and explore the scene with :
- Mouse Left : Rotate
- Mouse Right : Pan
- Mouse Middle : Zoom

I wrote an article about the project, with a technical breakdown of the piece at https://ulucode.com/wp/visa-to-the-stars/


Decent GPU REQUIRED, you can tune the performances with the "Quality" setting in the menu.
Better performances with Chrome.

Keyboard shortcuts:
SPACE : show/hide menu
A : toggle anti-aliasing
C : take a capture of the ccurrently selected resolution
R : reset camera position/orientation
S : display stats
P : pause animation

metadata.name: Mur #233
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Ripples #21
metadata.description:
Ripples - Made by Zoltan Szalay @insgraphizm with P5.js
April 2022, Hungary

Features
--------
7 color themes
Light or Dark background
Number of rings
Detail of noise

Keyboard control
----------------

[space] manually generate new composition
[a] automatically generate new composition
[s] save image

Touchscreen
-----------
Tap left edge to automatically or right edge to manually generate a new composition.

metadata.name: Balanced #110
metadata.description:
What does balance look like when viewed through the lens of pure mathematics? This is the question Balanced attempts to answer.

Each output is composed of a unique collection of blocks mathematically stacked to be in perfect balance.

This is my Genesis project. Enjoy!

Interactions:
1 - Reverse your stack vertically and re-balance.
2 - Toggle between square and portrait frame.
3 - Show center of mass. 
4 - Toggle the border.
5 - Toggle the background (color/transparent)
6 - Export image (2048x2048)
7 - Export image (4096x4096)
8 - Export image (8192x8192)

How it was made: https://www.jeffweber.art/balanced

metadata.name: Anachronous #264
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Horizon #103
metadata.description:
Horizon is made in the technique of "pointing". Each line consists of hundreds of dots.

Variations:

- 40% night and moon / 60% sun
- 30% colored lines. In this case you get unpredictable combinations. For example, a green moon and pink trees.
- 40% pier / 60% shore
- if there is a pier, 75% that there will be a tent on it
- different types of framing
- 15% singleton background and black lines

Please see variations.

______
by neigal 02.05.2022

metadata.name: Fax Abstraction #122
metadata.description:
The work was created from neurally generated with Latent Diffusion pictorial abstractions, which I was inspired by the work of Gerhard Richter.
They were further hybridized in the spirit of pointillism and Yayoi Kusama and the vintage fax art aesthetic.
Therefore, this work is about the friendship of different artistic styles coexisting together : )

Thanks Yulikolay for help in its creation!

metadata.name: Reconnaissance #221
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe they’re recon from another planet’s civilization — one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium “This is Mars,” Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands — and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for what’s next.


Choose a resolution (1-6) by adding "&scale=4" to the URL in live view.
Created with p5.js

TENDER x Nat Sarkissian
May 2022
